# range(start, stop, step)


# Parameters :::
    
# start → Number to start from (default is 0)

# stop → Number to stop before

# step → How much to increase each time (default is 1) 
                 #OR
#  step →means how much to jump each time. 


"""  NOTE 
Here we used list () in each eaxample .
list() is used to convert the range object into a list 
 allowing us to see all the numbers generated by range()."""


""""  NOTE  
# We use list() only when we want to see all the numbers
# generated by range() at once.
# In a for loop, list() is not needed because the for loop
# automatically reads the numbers from range() one by one."""


# EXAMPLE 1 :: 
# list(range(4))    # stop  (0,4) ::>>  0 (default)

# output : [0, 1, 2, 3]
  
# # EXAMPLE 2:: 
# list(range(1,6)) # range(start , stop) 

# output : [1, 2, 3, 4 ,5]
    
# #EXAMPLE 3:: 
""""Here, list() is used only to display all the values in the range object at once"""
# list(range(1,10,2)) # range(start , stop , step)  # step = step means how much to jump each time. 

# output : [1, 3, 5, 7, 9] jumped by 2 

